\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Given:
\series default
 connected binary matroid 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 with weighs 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{e}$
\end_inset

 for all elements 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Goal:
\series default
 find a disjoint union 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 of circuits of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{e\in C}w_{e}$
\end_inset

 is maximized
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Note:
\series default
 This includes the max cut problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Regular matroid decomposition theorem leads to:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Characterization of the cycle polytope
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Polyhedral approach for a special subclass: efficient separation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 optimization
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Section
From Definitions to Seymour's Decomposition Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Matroids: Main Definition
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 be a finite ground set
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}\subseteq2^{E}$
\end_inset

 be a family of subsets satisfying:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset\in\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 (non-empty)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
if 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B\in\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 (down-closed)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
if 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\in\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|<\left|B\right|$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A+x\in\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B\setminus A$
\end_inset

 (exchange property)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Then the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\left(E,\mathcal{I}\right)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
matroid
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Matroids: Key Notions
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A 
\series bold
base
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a maximal independent subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A 
\series bold
cobase
\series default
 is the set 
\begin_inset Formula $E-X$
\end_inset

 for some base 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\series bold
dual matroid
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{*}=\left(E,\mathcal{I}^{*}\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is all cobases and their subsets
\begin_inset VSpace 1em
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq E$
\end_inset

, the 
\series bold
rank
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the cardinality of a maximal independent subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A 
\series bold
circuit
\series default
 is a maximal dependent subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A 
\series bold
cocircuit
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
circuit
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $M^{*}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Graphic Matroids
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a graph with edge set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 be all forests in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Then the 
\series bold
graphic matroid
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $M=M\left(G\right)=\left(E,\mathcal{I}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A 
\series bold
cographic
\series default
 matroid is the dual of a graphic matroid
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A 
\series bold
planar
\series default
 matroid is one that is graphic and cographic
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Binary Matroids
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a binary matrix over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{GF}\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 with a column index set 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}$
\end_inset

 be all 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\subseteq E$
\end_inset

 such that the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 are independent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\series bold
binary matroid
\series default
 generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\left(E,\mathcal{I}\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace 1em
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Note:
\series default
 graphic matroids are binary (node-edge incidence matrix)
\begin_inset VSpace 1em
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Representation matrix:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Delete all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{GF}\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

-dependent rows from 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Perform binary row operations to arrive at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[I\mid B\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a representation matrix (can be empty)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Regular Matroids
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A real matrix is 
\series bold
totally unimodular
\series default
 (TU) if all its subdeterminants are 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A binary matroid is 
\series bold
regular
\series default
 if it has a representation matrix with a TU signing
\begin_inset VSpace 1em
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Important properties:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A binary matroid is regular iff every representation matrix has a TU signing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For a regular matroid, its dual and all its minors are regular
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Every graphic and cographic matroid is regular
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
